The program aims to reduce rural poverty in the regions of Timbuktu and Gao by restoring social networks and creating the conditions necessary to support economic activity. It exploits the hydro-agricultural potential of the Niger River. The interventions carried out under the program are concentrated in 14 communes located along the Niger River and five peripheral pastoral communes and concern small farmers, nomadic herders, rural women, young people and marginalized social groups.

The program aims to:

strengthen the capacity of local organizations and institutions to express their collective needs and to make and manage their investments; 
develop the agro-pastoral potential of the area in a sustainable way;
improving access to basic services through the development of community health centres;
contribute to the development of national policies to combat rural poverty;
promote policy dialogue to defend the interests of local rural communities.

The general objective of the project is to contribute to reducing rural poverty and improving food security. To do this, the project will support the strengthening of access to water resources for agricultural and pastoral use and their management.
Its specific objectives are:

build the capacities of target groups and encourage their participation in project activities, particularly through access to irrigated land;
assist target groups with investments to enhance their access to irrigation water through the use of technologies appropriate to their technical skills and resources;
intensify and diversify sustainable agricultural production under irrigation and in lowlands; And
support marketing and income-increasing activities, especially for the most asset-poor households.

The Gwadar-Lasbela Livelihoods Support Project will cover the two coastal districts of Gwadar and Lasbela in the province of Balochistan, where over 60 per cent of the population live in poverty.

The project will primarily target poor rural households in 382 villages in Gwadar and Lasbela, including small-scale landowners or landless tenants, small-scale fishers, and women. The project is expected to benefit about 20,000 rural households (116,000 people).

The project aims to increase the incomes and enhance the livelihoods of poor rural and fishers' households in the project area. In particular it will support:

Community development;
Fisheries development;
Rural infrastructure.
